03948nam a22005535i 9780822376064DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223760647 a10.1515/97808223760642doi  a(DE-B1597)554217  a(OCoLC)1224279007  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSCI0260002bisacsh  aMK 89002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123123:1 aCallison, Candis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Climate Change Comes to Matter :bThe Communal Life of Facts /cCandis Callison. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Inuit Gift -- t2. Reporting on Climate Change -- t3. Blessing the Facts -- t4. Negotiating Risk, Expertise, and Near-Advocacy -- t5. What Gets Measured Gets Managed -- tEPILOGUE. Rethinking Public Engagement and Collaboration -- tAppendix. A Decade of Climate Change -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the past decade, skepticism about climate change has frustrated those seeking to engage broad publics and motivate them to take action on the issue. In this innovative ethnography, Candis Callison examines the initiatives of social and professional groups as they encourage diverse American publics to care about climate change. She explores the efforts of science journalists, scientists who have become expert voices for and about climate change, American evangelicals, Indigenous leaders, and advocates for corporate social responsibility.The disparate efforts of these groups illuminate the challenge of maintaining fidelity to scientific facts while transforming them into ethical and moral calls to action. Callison investigates the different vernaculars through which we understand and articulate our worlds, as well as the nuanced and pluralistic understandings of climate change evident in different forms of advocacy. As she demonstrates, climate change offers an opportunity to look deeply at how issues and problems that begin in a scientific context come to matter to wide publics, and to rethink emerging interactions among different kinds of knowledge and experience, evolving media landscapes, and claims to authority and expertise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aClimatic changesxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxPress coveragexUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376064zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376064423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376064.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles